s. With Lionel Messi rested to help heal his right hamstring in time for Tuesday's first leg at Bayern Munich, Barcelona struggled to break through until Fábregas struck six minutes from time. The victory kept Barcelona on target to reclaim the Spanish title with a 13-point lead. Defender Eric Abidal played the full 90 minutes in his first start since February 2012.</p><p>Mesut Ozil scored twice for Real ahead of Wednesday's visit to Borussia Dortmund. The German worked a one-two with Karim Benzema for Madrid's opener in the 45th minute, before the France striker polished off a counterattack in the 57th from a pass by Cristiano Ronaldo. Ozil scored again in stoppage time after Jorge Molina had pulled one back with a penalty. Madrid's win came at a price, with injuries to Marcelo and Luka Modric. <strong>AP</strong></p><p></p><h2><strong>Lennon wants Celtic joy</strong></h2><p>Neil Lennon is looking for a \"joyous\" occasion at Celtic Park today as his <strong>Celtic</strong> side need one point to clinch the Scottish Premier League title against Inverness to secure the championship at home for the first time since April 2006. \"We haven't won it [the title] in front of our fans for a long, long time,\" the Celtic manager said. \"So it would be lovely to win the title in front of the home support. It should be joyous.\"</p><p><strong>Partick Thistle</strong> secured their return to the SPL as a 2-0 victory at <strong>Falkirk</strong> sealed the First Division title. More than 2,000 Thistle fans made the trip with their side needing only a point for promotion, and second-half goals from Andy Dowie and Chris Erskine proved enough. In Division Three, <strong>Rangers</strong> capped a difficult week off the field with a poor result on it as they slumped to a 2-1 home defeat against <strong>Peterhead</strong>. Lee McCulloch opened the scoring for the Light Blues but goals from Scott Ross and Rory McAllister sealed the win. The Blue Toon joined Annan Athletic as the only bottom-tier sides to take maximum points from the champions at Ibrox this season. <strong>PA</strong></p><h2><strong>Ferguson backs Wigan</strong></h2><p>Sir Alex Ferguson hopes Wigan win the FA Cup as a reward for Dave Whelan's loyalty. Whelan has transformed Wigan's fortunes since he took control in 1995. While they are again involved in a relegation scrap, they also have their first FA Cup final to look forward to on 11 May when they take on Manchester City. Even defeat would see the Latics qualify for Europe provided City do not collapse on the run-in and drop out of the Champions League places. But though he is anxious to state his feelings have nothing to do with City, Ferguson wants Wigan to be victorious at Wembley. \"I hope Wigan win the Cup – and not because it would be at the expense of Manchester City,\" Ferguson told United Review. \"In Dave Whelan they have an owner who has not only shown great faith in his manager, but someone who invests so much emotionally in his club.\" <strong>PA</strong></p><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" /><img width='1' height='1' src='http://guardian.co.uk.feedsportal.com/c/34708/f/639039/s/2af6ce2a/mf.gif' border='0'/><div class='mf-viral'><table border='0'><tr><td valign='middle'><a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/share/twitter/?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Ffootball%2F2013%2Fapr%2F20%2Ffootball-news-in-brief&t=Football+news+in+brief\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://res3.feedsportal.com/social/twitter.png\" border=\"0\" /></a>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://share.feedsportal.com/share/facebook/?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.guardian.co.uk%2Ffootball%2F2013%2Fapr%2F20%2Ffootb